column1: In order to have multiple connections (like in case of out-of-band connections) between the controller and a switch
column2: we need to have support for auxiliary channel in ONOS (defined in openflow spec 1.3);Epic;Open;Major;06/Nov/17 10:20 AM;06/Nov/17 10:20 AM;03/Oct/23 11:27 AM;Additional ports can be defined for Openflow channel due to various reasons (redundancy
column3: load balancing). Openflow connection established through additional ports is called auxiliary connection. By defining auxiliary connection
column4: we have multiple connections (Openflow channel) between a single switch and a controller.  In order to make OpenFlow communication via the auxiliary port
column5: the main channel connection must first be established. If the main channel connection is off
column6: the auxiliary connections are also cannot used. In case of functionally
column7: there is no difference between main channel connection and auxiliary connection.

Atomix 2.x timeouts;Bug;Closed;Blocker;08/Sep/17 6:56 PM;14/Sep/17 8:20 PM;03/Oct/23 11:27 AM;Prior to the 1.11 release
column2: a bug was discovered in the Atomix log compaction timer that prevented compaction from being rescheduled after completion. This meant that ONOS nodes could eventually run out of disk space by being filled up with Raft commit logs. That issue is now fixed in Atomix 2.0.0. However
column3: enabling more frequent log compaction has produced periodic pauses that cause arbitrary timeouts. We've rolled back the Atomix upgrade for the 1.11.0 release
column4: but compaction needs to be restored for 1.11.1 and 1.12 ASAP.

onos-app does not reinstall apps correctly;Bug;Open;Major;23/Aug/17 2:29 PM;23/Aug/17 2:29 PM;03/Oct/23 11:27 AM;"Using the onos-app utility to reinstall and reactivate an application fails.
1) Install an app using onos-app <IP> install! app.oar. This works as expected with no errors.
2) Reinstall the app using onos-app <IP> reinstall! app.oar. This doesn't work as expected and app reinstallation/reactivation fails.
3) Subsequent reinstalls don't change the behavior and the app installation/activation fails.
The same behavior is seen when doing this through the onos-cli. The feature is not properly unloaded/uninstalled as it shows up on running feature:list even after the app has been uninstalled
column2: while bundle:list and scr:list doesn't list the app."

NETCONF implementation should allow for setting timeouts individually on different devices;Bug;Resolved;Minor;24/Jul/17 3:44 PM;15/Aug/17 7:05 AM;03/Oct/23 11:27 AM;"NETCONF controller is configurable with 4 properties
* sshLibrary defaultValue=apache_mina ""Ssh Library instead of apache_mina (i.e. ethz-ssh2)""
* netconfIdleTimeout defaultValue=300 ""Time (in seconds) SSH session will close if no traffic seen""
* netconfConnectTimeout defaultValue=5 ""Time (in seconds) to wait for a NETCONF connect.""
* netconfReplyTimeout defaultValue=5 ""Time (in seconds) waiting for a NetConf reply""
The same value set applies to all devices connected through NETCONF.
This does not make sense in practice as the network will be made up of a number of high powered devices with fast response times
column2: and low powered devices with slower response times. Additionally some types of devices will not have regular polling
column3: and so will need to have a higher idle timeout.

column1: These 4 parameters should be configurable individually per device
column2: and have the ability to default to sensible values per device type."
